Given that $$f:(a,b) \to [1,\infty )$$<br/><br/>and $$g(x) = \left\{ {\matrix{
   0 & , & {x < a}  \cr 
   {\int_a^x {f(t)dt} } & , & {a \le x \le b}  \cr 
   {\int_a^b {f(t)dt} } & , & {x > b}  \cr 

 } } \right.$$<br/><br/>Now, $$g({a^ - }) = 0 = g({a^ + }) = g(a)$$<br/><br/>[as $$g({a^ + }) = \mathop {\lim }\limits_{x \to {a^ + }} \int_a^x {f(t)dt = 0} $$ and $$g(a) = \int_a^a {f(t)dt = 0} $$]<br/><br/>$$g({b^ - }) = g({b^ + }) = g(b) = \int_a^b {f(t)dt} $$<br/><br/>$$\Rightarrow$$ g is continuous, $$\forall$$x$$\in$$R.<br/><br/>Now, $$g'(x) = \left\{ {\matrix{
   0 & , & {x < a}  \cr 
   {f(x)} & , & {a < x < b}  \cr 
   0 & , & {x > b}  \cr 

 } } \right.$$<br/><br/>g'(a<sup>$$-$$</sup>) = 0 but g'(a<sup>+</sup>) = f(a) $$\ge$$ 1<br/><br/>[$$\because$$ Range of f(x) is [1, $$\infty$$), $$\forall$$ x $$\in$$[a, b]]<br/><br/>$$\Rightarrow$$ g is non-differentiable at x = a<br/><br/>and g'(b<sup>+</sup>) = 0<br/><br/>but g'(b<sup>$$-$$</sup>) = f(b) $$\ge$$ 1<br/><br/>$$\Rightarrow$$ g is not differentiable at x = b.

